    {
      "id": "02e61ea7c65fc787b7c7f013a042f247b438fd01",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 308,
        "name": "Amir Shehata",
        "email": "ashehata@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "ashehata"
      },
      "date": "2019-06-12 15:42:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1\n\nI think there is value in allowing the generic ip2nets syntax. This patch removes the ability to add a list of expressions on the command line and in YAML. You'll have to specify ip2nets parameter, which is there for backwards compatibility. The original intent was to standardize on that syntax because an explicit NID is a specific instance of the syntax.\n\nI think a better solution is to modify the code to handle different types of addresses. A function addr2nets can be created. The net in the NID can be extracted, and a lookup table implemented to lookup the type of net and call the appropriate address translation function. This will be useful if we add support for other types of addresses in the future.\n\nLook at libcfs_netstrfns in libcfs/libcfs/util/nidstrings.c\n\nThis way the appropriate address parsing function is called depending on the net type.\n\nThen we can allow:\nlnetctl peer add --nid 192.169.22.24@tcp,192.169.22.[75-78]@o2ib,[1-3]@gni",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
